AGI - At the beginning of the vaccination campaign against Covid-19, a group of doctors and researchers of the Irccs Foundation "Carlo Besta" (Fincb), of the Institute of Pharmacological Research "Mario Negri"- Irccs, of the Senese Hospitaller Company and of the Irccs Foundation Sollievo della Sofference, led by the Institute of Biomedical Technologies of the National Research Council of Segrate (Cnr-Itb), has joined forces to study the genetic bases of interindividual differences in the anti-correct response to anti-Covid-19 vaccination with the BNT162b2 vaccine (Pfizer-Btech).
The study showed that some subjects with certain genetic variants in the genes of the greater complex of istocompatibility (the properties of cells of a tissue to be recognized as their own by the body and therefore not to be eliminated by the immune system) involved in the main defense mechanisms of our immune system produced different quantities of antibodies directed against the antigen of the Sars-CoV-2 coronavirus. The study is available in open access on 'Communications Medicine'.
The group conducted a genetic association study at the level of the whole genome, evaluating the correlation between millions of genetic variants and antibody levels in the serum of subjects vaccinated against Covid-19, 30 days away from vaccination. In fact, since the beginning of the vaccination campaign, a substantial difference was observed in the amount of antibodies produced by vaccinated individuals. Genetists and immunologists immediately wondered what this difference was due to.&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"As for most medicines, so for vaccines every individual can respond more or less effectively and this is due, at least in part, to the individual genetic constitution," explains Francesca Colombo, researcher of the Cnr-Itb, who led the study. "Our study involved 1,351 subjects (vaccinated health workers in the first months of 2021, in the three hospital centers involved in the study), to which a blood sample was taken for the extraction of DNA and serum for the measurement of anti-Sars-CoV-2 antibodies after a month from the administration of the second dose of the Pfizer-Biontech vaccine," he added.
"With statistical analysis we found that a particular region of the genome, on chromosome 6, was significantly associated with antibody levels," adds Martina Esposito, the first author of the study and research fellow at Cnr-Itb. "In this specific genomic region there are genes that codify for molecules present on the cell surface, involved in immune response mechanisms. These genes - continuous - are very variable (they are the same that are evaluated when looking for compatibility between bone marrow donors, for example) and there are different combinations. Our study highlighted that some combinations were associated with higher levels of antibodies, while others at lower levels, thus explaining genetic differences in response to vaccination observed between different individuals."
Spiega Massimiliano Copetti, Head of Biostatistics of the Fondazione Irccs Casa Sollievo della Sofference: "The used mathematical models and statistical analyses carried out to achieve these results are very complex because complex is the interaction between the genes and genes themselves with the vaccine. Expertise gained in genetic studies in many years of research conducted at Casa Sollievo della Sofference allowed us to manage this complexity in data, helping to achieve these important results."
<div </div
&nbsp;
Adds Massimo Carella, biologist geneticist and deputy scientific director of the Fondazione Irccs Casa Sollievo della Sofference: "The identification of specific Hla alleles that give a predisposition to a high or low production of antibodies after the administration of the anti-Covid vaccine can now allow us to differentiate and customize the vaccination campaign, providing each individual the most suitable vaccine, that is what will allow him to produce as many antibodies as possible. This approach can also be extended to other vaccines designed against other diseases, with the aim of a precision vaccination supported by vaccinegenomics." Underline Colombo: "The results of our study confirm in part those already reported by an English group that has conducted research similar to ours but on subjects to which the vaccine produced by AstraZeneca was administered, and this is very important in genetic studies of this type, in which genetic differences between different populations can make it difficult to identify the variations really responsible for the biological phenomenon observed".
Concludes Raffaella Brugnoni, health researcher at the Department of Clinical Research and Development of the Foundation Irccs Istituto Neurologico Carlo Besta: "The strength of this research project lies in the active collaboration between the various partners and in its multicentric approach, to which we have contributed through the collection of biological material and the fundamental serological data for this study. It is an example of how different scientific communities can collaborate for the progress of joint research and well-being."
The collaboration at the national level of several centers has allowed the recruitment of a good number of subjects and the collection of its biological material, a fundamental aspect for genetic studies such as this, which by definition require numerous cases to obtain robust results. For this reason, researchers have already planned to share data produced with other international groups to obtain information on the genetic response to anti-Covid-19 vaccines, which can be valid for individuals not only of European origin, but also of other populations in the world.
The study also opens new paths to that precision medicine that is increasingly spoken of because, even in vaccines, knowledge of the genetic bases of a more or less effective response could allow a more targeted vaccination campaign, especially for the most fragile subjects. The research was funded by the Soka Gakkai Italian Buddhist Institute.
